     1	# Perf regression detection (0.7.2 PR-7)
     2	
     3	**Status:** landed (0.7.2 PR-7). Owns `dev/perf-history/` + the
     4	`perf-regression-check` binary (`fathomdb-cli` crate, layout (A) — a
     5	`[[bin]]` entry, NOT a new workspace crate).
     6	
     7	## Purpose
     8	
     9	Persist canonical-CI / release-time performance numbers per commit and
    10	surface regressions automatically with a deliberately **low false-positive
    11	rate**. The store is the ship-verdict history; the bin reads it, groups by
    12	`(ac_id, n)`, and compares the single most-recent run in each group against
    13	the rolling median of the prior runs in that group.
    14	
    15	## Append-only invariant
    16	
    17	`dev/perf-history/` is **append-only**. The `perf-regression-check` binary
    18	**only reads** the directory — it never writes, mutates, or deletes any
    19	file. New rows are written by CI (or by a human at release time, for the
    20	locally-measured AC-013 / AC-013b / AC-019 numbers). This keeps the history
    21	a tamper-evident, git-tracked audit trail: a regression is a new file whose
    22	numbers the bin flags, not an edit to an old file.
    23	
    24	## Record schema
    25	
    26	One JSON file per canonical run (filename convention:
    27	`<ac_id>-<commit_sha:8>-<n>.json`, e.g. `AC-013-c893d8b0-10000.json`). The
    28	bin globs `*.json` in the directory and parses each file as one record:
    29	
    30	```json
    31	{
    32	  "commit_sha": "c893d8b0",
    33	  "ac_id": "AC-013",
    34	  "n": 10000,
    35	  "p50_ms": 36.0,
    36	  "p99_ms": 49.0,
    37	  "recall": 0.937,
    38	  "timestamp": "2026-06-01T07:23:39Z"
    39	}
    40	```
    41	
    42	| field        | type            | required | notes |
    43	|--------------|-----------------|----------|-------|
    44	| `commit_sha` | string          | yes      | commit the run was measured at |
    45	| `ac_id`      | string          | yes      | `AC-012` \| `AC-013` \| `AC-013b` \| `AC-019` \| … |
    46	| `n`          | integer         | yes      | corpus row count; part of the grouping key |
    47	| `p50_ms`     | number          | no\*     | median latency; omit for recall-only ACs |
    48	| `p99_ms`     | number          | no\*     | tail latency; omit for recall-only ACs |
    49	| `recall`     | number \| null  | no       | recall@10; omit/null for latency-only ACs (AC-012, AC-019) |
    50	| `timestamp`  | RFC3339 string  | yes      | run time; used to pick the single latest run per group |
    51	
    52	\* A record must carry at least one comparable metric (a latency pair or a
    53	recall value), else it is malformed.
    54	
    55	**Forward-extensibility:** unknown fields are **ignored, not rejected**.
    56	Adding fields to the schema later does not break older readers or invalidate
    57	older files. (`serde` with default `deny_unknown_fields` OFF.)
    58	
    59	## Grouping — tier-aware
    60	
    61	Records are grouped by the **`(ac_id, n)`** pair. This is deliberate:
    62	
    63	- AC-013 @ N=10k is never compared against AC-013 @ N=100k (different
    64	  latency tier — see `ADR-0.7.0-text-query-latency-gates-revised.md`, the
    65	  10k binding tier vs the 100k/1M tracked tiers).
    66	- The real-corpus anchor (N=7667) is a **different group** from the
    67	  synthetic N=10000 run — real bge and synthetic isotropic data have
    68	  different absolute numbers and must not cross-contaminate a median.
    69	
    70	## Detection thresholds (HITL Gate 1 — LOCKED 2026-06-01)
    71	
    72	Per HITL sign-off on 2026-06-01, the thresholds are:
    73	
    74	| metric  | flag condition                                            |
    75	|---------|-----------------------------------------------------------|
    76	| latency | `p50` **or** `p99` degraded **> 15%** vs the rolling median |
    77	| recall  | recall degraded **> 0.03 absolute** vs the rolling median   |
    78	| window  | rolling median of the prior **up to 10** runs per group     |
    79	| latest  | the **single most-recent** run (by timestamp) per group     |
    80	
    81	**Rationale (false-positive resistance is the design priority — codex's
    82	review focus):**
    83	
    84	- Recall σ = **0.0116** (PR-3 measured, N=7667 anchor;
    85	  `0.7.2-PR-3-perf-data.md`). A **0.03** absolute threshold is ≈ **2.4σ**,
    86	  i.e. roughly a **~1% jitter false-flag rate** — the deliberate
    87	  low-cry-wolf choice. We would rather miss a marginal real drift than fire
    88	  on noise, because a fired flag costs human triage on every canonical run.
    89	- **Tradeoff acknowledged:** a 0.03 recall drop from the 0.937 anchor lands
    90	  at **0.907**, which is right above the **0.90** floor. So this threshold
    91	  favours **false-positive resistance over early-warning sensitivity**: a
    92	  recall decay that creeps toward the floor in <0.03 steps will not trip the
    93	  detector before it nears 0.90. That is an accepted limitation; the hard
    94	  recall floor is enforced separately by the AC-013b gate, not by this
    95	  drift detector.
    96	- **15% latency** allows for normal run-to-run variance on shared CI
    97	  hardware (the canonical runner is a 4-core EPYC slice; cold-cache and
    98	  neighbour-noise swing latency more than recall).
    99	
   100	The "latest = single most-recent run vs the median of the prior runs in the
   101	window" definition means a one-off bad run flags immediately (good for catch
   102	latency) but a single good run after a bad streak does not mask the streak
   103	(the median is robust to one outlier).
   104	
   105	## Insufficient history
   106	
   107	A group with **fewer than 2 runs** (i.e. no prior runs to form a median
   108	after removing the latest) is reported as **insufficient-history** — NOT a
   109	regression and NOT a crash. The AC-012 @ N=1M group is exactly this case
   110	today (one documented canonical run, v0.6.1 `603a4bc`).
   111	
   112	## Exit codes
   113	
   114	| code | meaning |
   115	|------|---------|
   116	| `0`  | no regression flagged (includes all-insufficient-history) |
   117	| `1`  | at least one group flagged a regression |
   118	| `2`  | data missing or malformed (directory absent, unreadable JSON, record with no comparable metric) |
   119	
   120	## Output
   121	
   122	- Default: human-readable report to stdout (one block per group; flagged
   123	  groups marked clearly).
   124	- `--json`: machine-parseable JSON object to stdout (per-group verdicts +
   125	  an overall `flagged` boolean), for CI to post as a comment.
   126	
   127	## CI integration (`.github/workflows/perf-canonical.yml`)
   128	
   129	After the AC-012 canonical run, the workflow builds and runs
   130	`perf-regression-check dev/perf-history/ --json`, captures stdout, and posts
   131	it as a comment on the triggering PR/push (via `actions/github-script`).
   132	
   133	- Exit **1** (regression flagged): the step **continues** — the comment is
   134	  the signal, not a hard failure. (A regression on a `workflow_dispatch`
   135	  diagnostic run should not red-X the run; a human reads the comment.)
   136	- Exit **2** (data integrity): the step **fails loudly** — malformed history
   137	  is a real defect in the store and must block.
   138	
   139	The workflow stays **`workflow_dispatch`-only** (no push/PR/schedule
   140	triggers added) and keeps within GitHub's workflow_dispatch input cap (≤ 8
   141	inputs, per the prior consolidation fix).
   142	
   143	## Backfill provenance
   144	
   145	The committed `dev/perf-history/` rows are backfilled from:
   146	
   147	- **AC-012 @ N=1M** — v0.6.1 canonical CI run `603a4bc` (run 26346417896,
   148	  2026-05-23): p50=140.95, p99=458, verdict RED (over the 20/150 ADR
   149	  budget). Source: `dev/notes/perf-canonical-runner-2026-MM.md`. **This is
   150	  the only documented AC-012 canonical run → its group is sparse
   151	  (insufficient history).** It is an honestly-RED historical point, not a
   152	  regression the detector should flag (no prior to compare against).
   153	- **AC-013 / AC-013b synthetic @ N=10000** — the 2026-05-27
   154	  PERF-VECTOR-QUANT arc, including the **batch-collapse bug** (`035cfa3`,
   155	  the buggy parent) and its **fix** (`4a95cfd`). Source:
   156	  `STATUS-perf-vector-quant.md`. The `035cfa3` row carries the honest
   157	  collapsed-state recall (**0.1572**, the documented measurement once the
   158	  collapse was made measurable) — a genuine recall regression vs the prior
   159	  healthy synthetic median; `4a95cfd` recovers (0.5124, Option-1 dense
   160	  isotropic). v0.7.0 (`38d5f4f`) anchors the synthetic latency/recall.
   161	- **AC-013 / AC-013b / AC-019 real bge @ N=7667** and **AC-013 synthetic @
   162	  N=10000** forward baseline — v0.7.1 / 0.7.2 (`c893d8b`, 2026-06-01) +
   163	  PR-3 local data. Source: `dev/plans/runs/0.7.2-PR-3-perf-data.md`.
   164	
   165	**Honesty note:** the v0.6.1 AC-012 @ N=1M run was a real **RED** verdict
   166	(7× over the p50 budget) — it is preserved faithfully in the store, not
   167	smoothed away. It does not flag as a *regression* only because it is the
   168	sole point in its group (insufficient history); its RED-ness is a separate
   169	budget fact recorded in `perf-canonical-runner-2026-MM.md`.

