1. Blocker: The committed backfill chronology is wrong. [AC-013b-38d5f4f0-10000.json](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/dev/perf-history/AC-013b-38d5f4f0-10000.json:1) timestamps `v0.7.0` at `2026-05-27T18:05:00Z`, earlier than [AC-013b-4a95cfd0-10000.json](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/dev/perf-history/AC-013b-4a95cfd0-10000.json:1) at `2026-05-27T20:00:00Z`, but git shows `4a95cfd` committed at `2026-05-27T16:54:27-05:00` and `38d5f4f` tagged `v0.7.0` at `2026-05-27T20:18:00-05:00`, so `38d5f4f` must sort after `4a95cfd`, not before it. That violates the “latest by timestamp” contract in [perf-regression-detection.md](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/dev/design/perf-regression-detection.md:50) and [perf-regression-detection.md](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/dev/design/perf-regression-detection.md:79). Fix: rewrite the backfill timestamps to preserve true commit/release chronology, and add a test on the committed 2026-05-27 arc instead of only the current clean-exit assertion in [perf_regression_check.rs](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-cli/tests/perf_regression_check.rs:140).

2. Blocker: Malformed timestamps are silently accepted, so “data integrity” failures do not actually fail loudly. [perf-regression-check.rs](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-cli/src/bin/perf-regression-check.rs:92) stores `timestamp` as a raw `String`, [load_record](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-cli/src/bin/perf-regression-check.rs:120) never parses it, and [build_report](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-cli/src/bin/perf-regression-check.rs:283) sorts lexically while assuming RFC3339. A bad value can therefore alter latest-run selection without returning exit 2, contrary to the schema/exit-code contract in [perf-regression-detection.md](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/dev/design/perf-regression-detection.md:50) and [perf-regression-detection.md](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/dev/design/perf-regression-detection.md:118). Fix: parse to a typed RFC3339 timestamp during load, reject parse failures with exit 2, and sort on the parsed value.

3. High: The CI integration’s non-failing regression signal is effectively dead on the only allowed trigger. The workflow remains `workflow_dispatch`-only [perf-canonical.yml](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/.github/workflows/perf-canonical.yml:33), exit 1 is intentionally swallowed in [the detector step](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/.github/workflows/perf-canonical.yml:165), but the comment step only runs when `github.event.pull_request.number` exists [perf-canonical.yml](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/.github/workflows/perf-canonical.yml:188). Manual dispatch payloads do not carry that field, so a flagged regression becomes log-only while the workflow still requests [pull-requests: write](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/.github/workflows/perf-canonical.yml:71). Fix: emit the report to `$GITHUB_STEP_SUMMARY` or another `workflow_dispatch`-safe channel and drop the PR-write permission unless a real PR event is introduced.

